Characteristics-driven returns in equilibrium

This notebook presents the code used for the paperCharacteristics-driven returns in equilibrium.
The dataset, with anonymized tickers, is available upon request.

1 Setup

First, we load packages & import the data.
The comments, preceded by hashtags # allow to change the set of characteristics (e.g., from 3 to 6).
Below, we work with 6 characteristics, so the results will differ from those of the paper.

library(tidyverse)                                      # Data wrangling package
library(lubridate)                                      # Date management
library(ggallin)                                        # Addin to ggplot for negative log scales
library(viridis)                                        # Cool color palette
library(patchwork)                                      # To layout graphs
library(plm)                                            # For panel model estimation
load("data_demand.RData")                               # Loading the data
data_demand <- data_demand %>% arrange(Stock_id, Date)  # Ordering
dates <- data_demand$Date %>% unique() %>% sort()
features <- c("Mkt_Cap", "P2B", "Mom", "Asset_growth", "Prof_Marg", "Vol_1M")

D_features <- c("D_Mkt_Cap", "D_P2B", "D_Mom", "D_Asset_growth", "D_Prof_Marg", "D_Vol_1M")

2 Initialization of variables

Below, we create the objects in which we will store some results. Also, we fix the sample size used throughout the notebook!

sample <- 60                                                                       # Sample size (in months)
dates_oos <- dates[sample:length(dates)]                                           # Out-of-sample dates
coefs_1 <- matrix(nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1, ncol = 2 * length(features) + 1)   # Initialize coefficients
t_stats_1 <- matrix(nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1, ncol = 2 * length(features) + 1) # Initialize t-statistics
R_1_pool <- matrix(0, ncol = 2, nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1)                      # Initialize R^2
cor_series <- array(0, dim = c(length(dates_oos)-1,                                # Initialize correlation matrices     
                               2 * length(features) + 1,
                               2 * length(features) + 1))
cov_series <- array(0, dim = c(length(dates_oos)-1,                                # Initialize covariance matrices     
                               2 * length(features) + 1,
                               2 * length(features) + 1))
coefs_1_p <- matrix(nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1, ncol = 2* length(features) )     # Coefs for within estimates
t_stats_1_p <- matrix(nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1, ncol = 2* length(features) )   # t-stats for within estimates
R_1_fixed <- matrix(0, ncol = 2, nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1)
f_e <- c()
avg_ret <- matrix(0, ncol = length(features), nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1)
avg_fe <- matrix(0, ncol = length(features), nrow = length(dates_oos) - 1)

3 Pooled estimation

The loop below perform 4 tasks:
1. perform the pooled estimations and store the corresponding estimates & metrics (e.g., \(R^2\)).
2. compute the correlations and covariances between the characteristics and their changes.
3. estimate the model with fixed effects & store the values.
4. compute the average return and average fixed effect of sorted portfolios on the rolling samples.

The code loops on the dates.
We could make do without a loop via the pmap() function.
But the complexity of the output is a bit deterring (this would generate a complex list).

NOTE: the inelegant code can take some time to run (5-30 minutes depending on the computer).

To compute some indicators, we define a custom function below.

sorted_metric <- function(data, var, metric){ 
  # This function computes the average metric of sorted portfolios for a given sample & char
  # The metric is either the return of the average fixed effect
  data %>% 
    mutate(Type = if_else(!!as.name(var) > 0, "Large", "Small")) %>%
    group_by(Date, Type) %>%
    summarise(met = mean(!!as.name(metric), na.rm = T)) %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = Type, values_from = met) %>%
    mutate(Premium = Large - Small) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    summarise(m = mean(Premium, na.rm = T)) %>% pull(m)
}

The loop:

for(i in 1:(length(dates_oos)-1)){
  if(i %% 60 == 0){print(dates_oos[i])}                                       # Keeps track of progress
  # The code below is for the simple estimation
  data_train_1 <- data_demand %>%                                             # Data with which the allocation is computed
    filter(Date <= dates_oos[i], Date >= dates[i]) %>%                        # ... it's filtered appropriately
    group_by(Stock_id) %>%
    mutate(Return = dplyr::lead(Return)) %>%                                  # ... incorporates the forward returns
    ungroup() %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    select(all_of(c(features, D_features, "Return", "Stock_id", "Date")))     # ... and the desired variables
  fit_1 <- lm(Return ~ ., data = data_train_1 %>% select(-Stock_id, -Date))   # Simple OLS estimation
  coefs_1[i,] <- summary(fit_1)$coef[,1]                                      # Keep the coefficients
  t_stats_1[i,] <- summary(fit_1)$coef[,3]                                    # Keep the t-stats
  R_1_pool[i,1] <- summary(fit_1)$r.squared[1]                                # Keep the R^2
  R_1_pool[i,2] <- summary(fit_1)$adj.r.squared[1]                            # Keep the adjusted R^2
  
  # Next we compute the correlations & covariances
  cor_series[i,,] <- cor(data_train_1 %>% select(-Stock_id, -Date), use = "pairwise.complete.obs")   # Store the correlation matrix
  cov_series[i,,] <- cov(data_train_1 %>% select(-Stock_id, -Date), use = "pairwise.complete.obs")   # Store the covariance matrix
  
  # The code below is the the pooled estimation
  fit_1 <- plm(Return ~ Mkt_Cap + P2B + Mom + Asset_growth + Prof_Marg + Vol_1M + 
                 D_Mkt_Cap + D_P2B + D_Mom + D_Asset_growth + D_Prof_Marg + D_Vol_1M,                # Panel model estimation
               data = data_train_1 %>% select(-Date), model = "within", index = "Stock_id")          # Model options
  coefs_1_p[i,] <- summary(fit_1)$coef[,1]
  t_stats_1_p[i,] <- summary(fit_1)$coef[,3]
  R_1_fixed[i,] <- summary(fit_1)$r.squared %>% as.numeric()
  f_e <- bind_rows(f_e, bind_cols(f_e = fixef(fit_1) %>% as.numeric(),                               # Store the fixed effects
                                  Date = dates_oos[i],
                                  Stock_id = unique(data_train_1$Stock_id) %>% sort())
  )
  
  # Finally, the average returns & average fixed-effects of the sorted portfolios
  for(j in 1:length(features)){
    avg_ret[i,j] <- sorted_metric(data_train_1, features[j], "Return")                               # Store the average return
    avg_fe[i,j] <- sorted_metric(data = bind_cols(f_e = fixef(fit_1) %>% as.numeric(),               # Store the fixed effects
                                                  Stock_id = unique(data_train_1$Stock_id) %>% sort()) %>%
                                   left_join(data_train_1, by = "Stock_id"), 
                                 var = features[j], 
                                 metric = "f_e")
  }
  
}

5 Anomaly decomposition

In the paper, we decompose the average return of sorted portfolios into three terms:
1. the average fixed effect (not explained by characteristics)
2. the loading on the characteristic of the sort
3. interaction terms

Below, we compute the first two, along with rolling average windows.
The grey curve is equal to the average return minus the first two terms.

avg_exp <- bind_rows(
  avg_ret %>%
    `colnames<-` (c("Size", "Value", "Momentum", "Inv", "Prof", "Vol")) %>%
    data.frame() %>% 
    bind_cols(data.frame(Date = dates_oos[1:(length(dates_oos)-1)])) %>%
    pivot_longer(-Date, names_to = "Factor", values_to = "value") %>% 
    mutate(Series = "Avg_Return"),
  
  bind_cols(Date = dates_oos[1:(length(dates_oos)-1)]) %>%
    data.frame(Size = coefs_1_p$Mkt_Cap,
               Value = coefs_1_p$P2B,
               Momentum = coefs_1_p$Mom,
               Inv = coefs_1_p$Asset_growth,
               Prof = coefs_1_p$Prof_Marg,
               Vol = coefs_1_p$Vol_1M) %>%
    pivot_longer(-Date, names_to = "Factor", values_to = "value") %>%
    mutate(Series = "Beta", value = value *4/sqrt(2*3.14)),
  
  data.frame(Size = avg_fe[,1], 
             Value = avg_fe[,2], 
             Momentum = avg_fe[,3],
             Inv = avg_fe[,4],
             Prof = avg_fe[,5],
             Vol = avg_fe[,6]) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Date = dates_oos[1:(length(dates_oos)-1)])) %>%
    pivot_longer(-Date, names_to = "Factor", values_to = "value") %>% 
    mutate(Series = "Lambda")
) 
avg_exp %>%
  ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = value, linetype = Series, size = Series), color = "black") +
  scale_size_manual(values = c(0.3,0.5,0.7)) +  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        axis.title.y = element_blank()) +
  geom_line(data = avg_exp %>% pivot_wider(names_from = Series, values_from = value) %>% mutate(Residual = Avg_Return - Beta - Lambda),
            aes(x = Date, y = Residual),
            color = "grey", size = 0.99) +
    geom_line(data = avg_exp %>% filter(Series == "Avg_Return" ),
            aes(x = Date, y = value),
            color = "blue", size = 0.5) +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(Factor), scales = "free")

6 The dispersion of sample means

The graph below shows that, as sample size increases, the dispersion of sample means decreases.
We compare 12 month versus 60 month samples.

disp_sample <- data_demand %>%
  mutate(year = year(Date),
         half_dec = round(year(Date)/5)) %>%
  group_by(year, Stock_id) %>%
  mutate(avg_12 = mean(Return, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  mutate(sd_12 = sd(avg_12, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(half_dec, Stock_id) %>%
  mutate(avg_60 = mean(Return, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(half_dec) %>%
  mutate(sd_60 = sd(avg_60)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("sd_12", "sd_60"), names_to = "type", values_to = "value") 

disp_sample_light <- disp_sample[!duplicated(disp_sample %>% select(year, type, value)),]

disp_sample_light %>%
  filter(year < 2021) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = value, color = type)) + geom_line() + 
  geom_point() + theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(name = "Sample size", values = c("#000000", "#999999"), labels = c("12 months", "60 months")) + 
  theme(legend.position = c(0.8,0.8),
        text = element_text(size = 15),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        axis.title.y = element_blank())
